A bare 'No rule to make target blah' in a big build is undiagnosable.
When dependency analysis finds no rule for a needed target, it now
records every implicit rule whose output pattern DOES match and the
first prerequisite that disqualified it, and the error prints them:

  *kati*: note: candidate pattern rule '%.o: %.c' at Makefile:3
      rejected: needs 'prog.c', which does not exist and has no rule
  *kati*: note: 'prog.o' comes from the prerequisite list of the rule
      for 'all' at Makefile:2
  *** No rule to make target 'prog.o', needed by 'all'.

Capped at 4 candidates; the '*kati*:' prefix keeps corpus GNU-parity
(normalizers strip it). Both corpora stay fail=0.

